[1014|2220] 18:00:37.485 I/NARR-STATE: narrationState → Speaking(segment=NarrationSegment(id=poi_narration_1094665868979783, text=You're standing in front of a building that's seen Salem transform. While today it welcomes visitors to the National Historic Site, this brick armory began as a Works Progress Administration project in 1938 – the very first National Historic Site established in the United States. It was built to preserve and interpret the history of the 1692 Witch Trials, a dark chapter that still echoes through these streets. The WPA put men and women back to work during the Depression, and their craftsmanship is still visible in the brickwork, even as it's being carefully restored today. Notice the solid, functional design. This wasn't meant to be ornate; it was meant to be a civic building, a place where Salem could confront its past and present itself to the world. The masons are currently working to preserve the original brick, ensuring that this building continues to stand as a testament to Salem's complex story for generations to come., type=HINT, poiName=Salem Armory Regional Visitor Center, voiceId=en-us-x-tpd-local, kind=POI, category=null, refId=poi_narration, isReplay=false)) (autoPlay=true, queueSize=0)
