[2321|2220] 18:03:31.473 I/NARR-STATE: narrationState → Speaking(segment=NarrationSegment(id=poi_narration_1094841145734948, text=Look closely at the dark timbers and the small windows. You're standing before one of the oldest houses in Salem — and one of the earliest museums in the country. The John Ward House began as a home around 1684, just a few decades after the town itself was founded. That's nearly 340 years of stories held within these walls. It's a remarkable example of what's called 'First Period' architecture, meaning it was built by the very first English settlers. Notice how low to the ground it sits, and the steep roofline — designed to shed the heavy New England snows. In the early 20th century, the house was painstakingly restored by George Francis Dow, a pioneer in historic preservation. He didn't just fix it up; he researched how it *originally* looked, and brought those details back to life. Today, the Peabody Essex Museum owns and operates it, offering a glimpse into the lives of those who first built Salem. The house was designated a National Historic Landmark in 1968, recognizing its importance to our nation's history. Imagine the families who gathered here, the candles flickering in the long winter nights, the scent of woodsmoke and salt air drifting in from the harbor., type=HINT, poiName=John Ward House, voiceId=en-us-x-tpd-local, kind=POI, category=null, refId=poi_narration, isReplay=false)) (autoPlay=true, queueSize=0)
